intro: Anacis auriculata, commonly known as the auriculate anacis, is a flowering plant native to certain regions of Australia. It belongs to the family Apiaceae, which includes caraway and parsley, and is characterized by its finely divided leaves. The plant produces small, yellowish flowers that are clustered in umbels, a typical feature of the family. Anacis auriculata is often found in dry, sandy soils and is adapted to arid environments. Its botanical features make it an interesting subject for study in ecological and horticultural contexts.
